What is resistance

Resistance is the opposition to the flow of electric current in a circuit. It is measured in ohms and is caused by factors such as the material of the conductor, the temperature of the conductor, and the presence of external forces. Resistance is important because it determines the amount of current that flows through a circuit and the amount of energy that is wasted as heat.

Sure, here is some additional information about resistance:

Point 1: Temperature and Resistance

Resistance changes with temperature. As a conductor heats up, its resistance decreases, and as it cools down, its resistance increases. This is because the atoms in the conductor become more widely spaced as they heat up, causing them to conduct electricity less well.

Point 2: Types of Resistance

There are two main types of resistance: 

* Ohmic resistance: This is the resistance that occurs in a conductor due to the flow of current. It is measured in ohms and depends on the material of the conductor, as well as the temperature and length of the conductor.
* Frictional resistance: This is the resistance that occurs when a charged particle is moved through a conductor. It is measured in volts and depends on the material of the conductor and the speed at which the charged particle is moving.
